---
import MarketingLayout from '@/layouts/MarketingLayout.astro';
import { Nav } from '@/components/chrome/nav';
import { Footer } from '@/components/chrome/footer';
import { Eyebrow } from '@/components/ui/eyebrow';
import { ClosingCTASection } from '@/components/home/closing-cta-section';

export const prerender = true;
---

<MarketingLayout
    title="Our Story · Travelity"
    description="Why we built Travelity, who we're for, and what we're trying to make happen for inbound tourism."
>
    <Nav />

    <main class="bg-paper">
        <!-- Hero strip -->
        <section
            class="border-b border-line py-16 md:py-24"
            style="background: radial-gradient(ellipse 60% 50% at 50% 0%, hsl(var(--travelity-teal) / 0.08) 0%, transparent 60%), hsl(var(--paper));"
        >
            <div class="container mx-auto px-6 max-w-[820px] text-center">
                <Eyebrow withRule centered>Our story</Eyebrow>

                <h1
                    class="font-serif font-semibold text-ink leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.035em] mt-5 mb-5"
                    style="font-size: clamp(36px, 5vw, 56px);"
                >
                    Built by people who've
                    <em class="not-italic">
                        <span class="italic font-medium text-travelity-teal"
                            >run a tour business.</span
                        >
                    </em>
                </h1>

                <p
                    class="text-[18px] text-ink-muted leading-[1.55] max-w-[60ch] mx-auto"
                >
                    Travelity is a booking and operations platform for the
                    people the existing tools forgot — independent operators
                    running real businesses in places the big software companies
                    don't visit.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Lighter TODO banner — narrative is editable copy, not legal -->
        <div
            class="bg-[hsl(38_92%_50%/0.06)] border-b border-[hsl(38_92%_50%/0.2)]"
        >
            <div class="container mx-auto px-6 max-w-[820px] py-3">
                <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                    <span
                        class="font-mono text-[10.5px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.10em] text-[hsl(38_92%_40%)] flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"
                    >
                        Draft
                    </span>
                    <p
                        class="font-body text-[12.5px] text-ink-muted leading-[1.5] m-0"
                    >
                        AI-drafted narrative pending replacement with the real
                        founder story. Themes and structure can stay; specifics
                        about people, places, and timing should be revised by
                        Travelity's team before launch.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Body: long-form prose -->
        <article
            class="legal-prose container mx-auto px-6 max-w-[720px] py-16 md:py-20"
        >
            <h2>Why this exists</h2>
            <p>
                Travelity started in a Yerevan apartment in late 2024 with a
                simple complaint and a stack of spreadsheets. A friend ran a
                small tour operation — Garni-Geghard one day, the wineries
                another, custom multi-day trips when groups asked. Bookings came
                in via WhatsApp, GetYourGuide, his website, and the office
                phone. Capacity got tracked in a spreadsheet that nobody trusted
                by Friday.
            </p>
            <p>
                We looked at the booking platforms aimed at tour operators. They
                were either built for European day-tour aggregators with no
                useful concept of multi-day, or built for North American
                activity providers with assumptions that didn't survive contact
                with how Caucasus operators actually work — multi-currency,
                mixed product types, OTA marketplaces nobody had heard of in
                California.
            </p>
            <p>
                So we started building. Not because the world needs another
                booking platform — it doesn't — but because the people we know
                who run these businesses deserve software that takes their work
                seriously.
            </p>

            <h2>Who we're for</h2>
            <p>
                Travelity is built for the operators who keep travel running in
                places the big platforms can't be bothered with: tour operators
                in Yerevan, transfer providers in Tbilisi, accommodation hosts
                in Dilijan, independent guides who lead groups through
                landscapes that don't fit a category checkbox.
            </p>
            <p>
                You probably outgrew spreadsheets. You probably outgrew the SaaS
                that came after spreadsheets. You probably know more about your
                operation than any software vendor will ever ask. We're building
                Travelity for that level of expertise — software that adapts to
                your shape, not the other way around.
            </p>

            <h2>What we believe</h2>
            <p>A few principles guide what we build:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Your inventory is the product.</strong> Channels are just
                    where it shows up. The platform's first job is to never sell something
                    that doesn't exist.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Your data belongs to you.</strong> You can export everything
                    as CSV at any time. We will never make leaving harder than joining.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Operations beat sales.</strong> The slickest booking funnel
                    is worthless if Tuesday morning is chaos. We build for what 8am
                    looks like, not what the demo deck looks like.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Boring works.</strong> Software that runs the same on
                    Tuesday as it did on Monday is a feature, not a bug. We optimize
                    for predictability.
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Where we are</h2>
            <p>
                We're a small team — engineers, a designer, and a couple of
                people who've worked the operator side themselves. We're
                headquartered as BraveCrew Inc. and our infrastructure is hosted
                in the European Union (Frankfurt). Our customers are mostly in
                Armenia, Georgia, and the surrounding region for now, but the
                platform doesn't care where you operate; it cares whether the
                shape of your business fits the shape of the software.
            </p>
            <p>
                We're not VC-backed. We're funded by customer revenue and modest
                founder investment. We're growing steadily, hiring slowly, and
                building deliberately.
            </p>

            <h2>What's next</h2>
            <p>
                We have a roadmap, but it's short. The next year is about
                finishing the integrations operators have asked for (more OTAs,
                more payment methods, more languages), expanding the back-office
                to handle larger teams, and making the product easier to set up
                so onboarding is days, not weeks.
            </p>
            <p>
                If you run a travel business and you've read this far, we'd like
                to meet you. <a href="/book-demo">Book a demo</a> or <a
                    href="/contact">drop us a line</a
                > — we read everything, and we reply.
            </p>
        </article>

        <ClosingCTASection />
    </main>

    <Footer />
</MarketingLayout>
